      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interest on your student loan can be a bit tricky to grasp, but I'll try to break it down for you. You see, the interest on your loan is like a constant, sneaky thief, always lurking in the shadows, waiting to snatch away your hard-earned cash. It's like a little band of goblins, each one representing a fraction of a percent, working together to drain your account. The more you pay, the more they'll take, but the principal balance will still creep up, like a slow-moving, slimy creature from the depths of the forest.\n\nNow, let's talk about how the interest works with your monthly payments. When you make a payment, the interest is calculated on the outstanding balance, not on the original loan amount. This means that if you're making payments on time, the interest will be calculated on the new balance, which will be slightly higher than the previous one. It's like the goblins are always adapting, finding new ways to increase their share of your loot.\n\nThe reason the principal balance isn't moving as much as you'd like is because the interest is being applied to the principal, not just the interest itself. This is known as \"interest accrual.\" It's",
